WEBVTT

1
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:10,500
Dr. Rivera: Welcome back everyone. Let's start by checking in. What did you notice during your home practice this week?

2
00:00:12,100 --> 00:00:28,400
Participant A: Honestly it was really hard. The pain just dominated everything. I can't stop thinking about it — it's always there, pulling my attention no matter what I try to do. It's like my whole world is just the pain signal.

3
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:45,200
Dr. Rivera: Thank you for sharing that. That makes sense at this stage. What you're describing — that the pain is capturing your attention completely — that IS the beginning of the practice. Recognizing where attention goes is the first step.

4
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:58,800
Participant B: For me it was different. When the flare started I just breathed really hard, almost like I was trying to push the feeling away, drown it out with the breath. I don't know if that's right.

5
00:01:00,500 --> 00:01:10,000
Dr. Rivera: That's a really important observation. The mind uses attention as a kind of escape hatch. What do you think happens to the pain when you push against it that way?

6
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:20,500
Participant B: It kind of comes back harder. Like it gets louder when I try to shut it out.

7
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Dr. Rivera: Exactly. That's how attention works — resisting amplifies. What if instead of pushing away you tried simply staying with the sensation? Has anyone tried that?

8
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:55,600
Participant A: A little bit, yes. On Wednesday I tried to stay with the aching in my lower back. I kept my attention on it, and every time my mind wandered I gently brought it back. It was uncomfortable but I didn't feel as overwhelmed.

9
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:05,500
Dr. Rivera: That's a really important observation. You were practicing volitional attention — choosing where to place it. How will you carry that into this coming week?

10
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Participant A: I want to try it in the mornings before I even get out of bed. Just spend a few minutes with whatever is there without judging it.

11
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:28,000
Dr. Rivera: Perfect. That's exactly how to build the habit. Participant B, anything you'd like to try differently?

12
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:42,000
Participant B: Maybe I'll try not doing the hard breathing thing and just watch what happens. See if the pain actually changes on its own.

13
00:02:43,500 --> 00:02:52,000
Dr. Rivera: That curiosity is the practice. Well done today, both of you. See you next week.

